The John Hancock Vitality Program
A new approach to life insurance that helps protect your financial future while rewarding you for living a healthy life.









How the Program Benefits You:







Save Money
Save as much as 15% on your annual premium and up to $600 per year when you buy healthy food at the grocery store. Plus, earn thousands of dollars in other rewards.







Get Rewarded
Earn discounts, gift cards, and rewards from Apple, Amazon, Hyatt, iTunes, REI, Royal Caribbean International, Whole Foods, and other travel, entertainment, shopping, and fitness brands for the everyday things you do to stay healthy.







Live Healthy
Receive personalized health goals, expert nutrition information, wellness tips, resources, and more. These are just a few ways the program supports healthy living. You’ll even get a free Fitbit® device to get you started.



How it Works







Introducing John Hancock Vitality
See how John Hancock Vitality can protect the people you love, save you money and reward you for the everyday things you do to stay healthy.











 Program Highlights: 






NEW Vitality Active Rewards with Apple Watch®
Earn Apple Watch Series 2 for as little as $25 simply by being more active. Whether you enjoy walking, running, biking or swimming, the more active you are, the more Vitality Points you’ll earn towards funding the full cost of your watch.
Learn More











HealthyFood™ Benefit
With the Vitality HealthyFood™ benefit, you can save money every time you purchase healthy foods at more than 16,000 participating grocery stores nationwide, including Walmart® and 70 major grocery chains that are part of the NutriSavings™ network.
Learn More











Vitality Age Calculator
See how your healthy habits and lifestyle are impacting your life! Americans are, on average, five years older than their actual age, due to a number of health and wellness factors.  Your Vitality Age gives you a snapshot of your overall health, based on lifestyle choices, including your diet and exercise habits, and clinical factors such as cholesterol and blood pressure. The good news is that a few small lifestyle changes can yield big results!
Get Started













